WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.360
Hi, my name is John Harmon. I run the R4DS online learning community. Our community operates

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:18.059
primarily through a Slack team, and we invite R learners at all skill levels to join us

00:00:18.059 --> 00:00:26.660
at r4ds.io slash join. Among other things, we host book clubs for R-related books. Whenever

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:31.559
we start a new cohort for one of the book clubs, we need to find a time that works for

00:00:31.559 --> 00:00:37.880
as many of the people interested in reading the book as we can. We used to use a generic

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:44.200
free online app for everyone to sign up. Everyone would type in their name, choose their available

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:50.400
times and days, and then set a password in case they wanted to edit their selections.

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:55.020
Sometimes people would sign up twice, not remembering that John who was signed up already

00:00:55.020 --> 00:01:00.099
was them. At least one time, someone had a typo in their name, so when they came back

00:01:00.099 --> 00:01:04.900
to change their available hours, it counted as a new person. And of course, sometimes

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:09.739
we legitimately had multiple people with the same name signing up, so I didn't have any

00:01:09.739 --> 00:01:16.580
way to sort out who was who and how many duplicates we had. And even when everything went smoothly,

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:22.699
I didn't have an easy way to connect the information in that app to their Slack user, so I couldn't

00:01:22.699 --> 00:01:27.660
contact people directly to let them know that a cohort was being created at a time

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:34.220
they'd chosen. So I figured we already all have logins to the R4DS Slack. What if we

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:40.779
made our own app in Shiny and then connected that to the Slack API? Then the app could

00:01:40.779 --> 00:01:48.360
talk to our Slack and connect each user to their identity on R4DS. I posted the idea

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:54.519
on our Slack, and one of our users, Priyanka Gagnija, volunteered to make the initial app

00:01:54.519 --> 00:02:00.199
minus the login, and then I focused on the login part. I'd already done some work with

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:06.400
Yanni CD on his Slack teams package, which allows you to talk to Slack through R. You

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:15.000
can find that and Yanni's whole Slackverse family of packages on GitHub at YanniCD. My

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:22.360
goal was to take what I did there with interactive Slack authorization, make it work in Shiny,

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:28.639
and then wrap that up into an easy-to-use package. So this is what that looks like.

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:35.080
If you aren't already logged in, it asks you to log in using Slack. From that initial screen,

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:39.759
you're taken to Slack's permission screen to connect to your Slack account, and then

00:02:39.759 --> 00:02:44.919
it returns you to the Shiny app. Here we just use the connection to identify the user, but

00:02:44.919 --> 00:02:48.759
I have another app where we use it to make sure the user has permission to see certain

00:02:48.759 --> 00:02:54.080
messages, and I'm working on one that will help users ask better questions and then post

00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:59.839
those questions as them. So it works. Now let's see how I did on the easy-to-use part

00:02:59.839 --> 00:03:06.399
of the goal. You can install this from GitHub at R4DS slash Shiny Slack. This is one of

00:03:06.399 --> 00:03:11.320
the ways we can launch a normal Shiny app. We define a UI, define a server function,

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:17.240
and wrap them in Shiny's Shiny app function. Now we'll use Shiny Slack to add a Slack

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:24.080
login to that app. We replace Shiny's Shiny app with Shiny Slack's Shiny Slack app.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:31.199
We also need to give it the code that identifies our Slack team. And that's it. Well, kinda.

00:03:31.199 --> 00:03:35.759
So you probably want to deploy your app to something like shinyapps.io, not just run

00:03:35.759 --> 00:03:41.039
the app locally. And to do that, you'll need your own Slack app that has permission to

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:47.679
send people to apps hosted on your Shiny apps account. When I first started working on this,

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:53.000
setting up the Slack side of things was really complicated. I was kind of dreading explaining

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.160
this part. I mean, I just did that thing showing you how easy it is to set up the Shiny side

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:04.800
of this, and this part was going to ruin that. But then something magical happened. Slack

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:10.160
added an option to create a Slack app from something called a manifest. So I added a

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:15.720
function over in Slack teams, create custom app to make that easy. There's a vignette

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:21.600
explaining it, but basically you call create custom app with a couple arguments and copy

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.720
paste the result into Slack's app creation form. And with that, you can wrap your Shiny

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:31.760
app with Shiny Slack and integrate it with your Slack team. If you'd like to learn more,

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:37.760
stop by the R4DS Slack at r4ds.io slash join. We're putting together a new club where we

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:42.119
walk through side projects like this, so you can learn all about how this works under the

00:04:42.119 --> 00:04:43.040
hood over there.

